// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//  Pre-Rotation Assessment — organized by week for per-week pre-quizzes
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

export const PRE_QUIZ_BY_WEEK = {
  1: [
    { q:"A 62-year-old with proteinuric CKD is started on lisinopril. Over two weeks, her eGFR falls 12% and she feels well. Lisinopril produces this predictable drop in GFR by acting on which nephron structure?",
      choices:["The afferent arteriole (dilation)","The efferent arteriole (dilation)","The thick ascending limb","The principal cells of the collecting duct"], answer:1,
      explanation:"ACEi/ARBs dilate the efferent arteriole → reduce intraglomerular pressure → modest, hemodynamic drop in GFR. Up to ~30% Cr rise is expected and actually reflects the drug working. Knowing the nephron segments lets you predict drug effects in the clinic." },
    { q:"A cachectic 74-year-old woman with bilateral lower-extremity amputations has a serum Cr of 0.7 and a calculated CKD-EPI eGFR of 92. You need to dose gentamicin. Which is the most appropriate?",
      choices:["Dose based on the calculated eGFR of 92","Obtain a cystatin C-based eGFR or measured creatinine clearance","Use Cockcroft-Gault with her actual body weight","Give a standard empiric dose without adjustment"], answer:1,
      explanation:"Creatinine is a product of muscle turnover. In low-muscle-mass patients (amputees, sarcopenia, spinal cord injury), a 'normal' Cr overestimates GFR and leads to aminoglycoside toxicity. Cystatin C (produced by all nucleated cells) or a measured CrCl is more reliable." },
    { q:"A 58-year-old man is admitted for pneumonia. His admission Cr is 0.8. Thirty-six hours later, Cr is 1.2 — still flagged 'within normal range' by the lab. Does he meet KDIGO AKI criteria?",
      choices:["No — Cr is within the reference range","Yes — Cr rose ≥0.3 mg/dL within 48h, meeting Stage 1","No — he needs to meet the 1.5× baseline criterion","Cannot determine without urine output data"], answer:1,
      explanation:"KDIGO Stage 1 AKI: ≥0.3 mg/dL rise in 48h OR ≥1.5× baseline in 7d OR UOP <0.5 mL/kg/h for 6h. The absolute 'normal range' number is a trap — a 0.8 → 1.2 rise is a meaningful GFR drop (Cr-GFR is non-linear) and counts as AKI. Don't let a 'normal' Cr fool you." },
    { q:"A 65-year-old with 3 days of vomiting has Cr 2.4 (baseline 1.0), UNa 8 mEq/L, FENa 0.3%, BUN/Cr 32, and a bland urine sediment. Most likely mechanism?",
      choices:["Acute tubular necrosis","Pre-renal AKI","Post-renal obstruction","Acute interstitial nephritis"], answer:1,
      explanation:"Low UNa, FENa <1%, BUN/Cr >20, and bland sediment all point to pre-renal physiology — the kidneys are intact but underperfused, avidly reabsorbing sodium to defend volume. Volume repletion is both diagnostic and therapeutic." },
    { q:"A patient had prolonged intraoperative hypotension. Post-op Cr rises from 1.0 to 2.8. UA shows muddy brown granular casts and tubular epithelial cells; FENa is 3.5%. What is the expected course?",
      choices:["Recovery within 24 hours with fluid resuscitation","Recovery over days to weeks with supportive care","Rapid progression to ESRD within one month","Requires empiric high-dose steroids"], answer:1,
      explanation:"Muddy brown casts + FENa >2% after an ischemic insult = established ATN. Unlike pre-renal AKI (reversible within hours of volume restoration), ATN requires time for tubular regeneration — typically days to weeks. Care is supportive; avoid further nephrotoxins." },
    { q:"A 25-year-old presents with tea-colored urine 10 days after an upper respiratory infection. Dipstick: 3+ blood, 2+ protein. Microscopy shows dysmorphic RBCs and RBC casts. This urinary finding localizes pathology to the:",
      choices:["Bladder","Ureter","Glomerulus","Renal pelvis"], answer:2,
      explanation:"RBC casts form only when erythrocytes cross a damaged glomerular basement membrane and are trapped in Tamm-Horsfall protein within tubules. Dysmorphic RBCs reinforce a glomerular source. Together, these findings are the classic signature of glomerulonephritis." },
    { q:"A 70-year-old with anemia, back pain, and rising Cr has a negative urine dipstick for protein. A 24-hour urine collection shows 5 g of protein. Which test is most likely to reveal the underlying mechanism?",
      choices:["Repeat urine dipstick","Renal ultrasound","Serum and urine protein electrophoresis with immunofixation","Cystatin C-based eGFR"], answer:2,
      explanation:"The dipstick detects albumin, not light chains. A discrepancy between a negative dipstick and significant quantitative proteinuria is the classic clue for overflow proteinuria from monoclonal light chains (multiple myeloma, AL amyloid). SPEP/UPEP with immunofixation identifies the paraprotein." },
  ],
  2: [
    { q:"A 58-year-old on fluoxetine for depression presents with Na⁺ 126, serum osm 268, urine osm 510, urine Na 48. She is clinically euvolemic. Morning cortisol and TSH are normal. Most likely etiology?",
      choices:["Psychogenic polydipsia","Medication-induced SIADH","Adrenal insufficiency","Beer potomania"], answer:1,
      explanation:"The pattern is classic SIADH: euvolemic, hypo-osmolar plasma, inappropriately concentrated urine (>100), urine Na >40. Beer potomania has low urine osm (<100). Once cortisol and TSH are normal, medications become a leading cause — SSRIs are a common culprit. Stopping the offending drug often corrects the sodium." },
    { q:"A 70-year-old with chronic alcohol use is admitted with Na⁺ 108. Overnight she receives IV fluids, and 18 hours later Na is 124. Two days later, she develops dysarthria, dysphagia, and locked-in-like features. What has occurred?",
      choices:["Cerebral edema from under-correction","Osmotic demyelination syndrome from overcorrection","Wernicke's encephalopathy","Hepatic encephalopathy"], answer:1,
      explanation:"Na rose 16 mEq/L in 18h — well beyond the 6–8 mEq/24h ceiling for chronic hyponatremia. High-risk patients (Na <105, alcoholism, malnutrition, hypokalemia) are especially vulnerable to ODS, which classically appears days after the correction as progressive pontine/extrapontine signs. If overcorrection is detected early, re-lowering with D5W ± desmopressin can mitigate risk." },
    { q:"A dialysis patient with K⁺ 7.0 and peaked T waves receives IV calcium gluconate. Twenty minutes later, the repeat K⁺ is still 7.0. What is the correct interpretation?",
      choices:["Treatment failed — give another dose of calcium","Expected — calcium stabilizes the cardiac membrane but does not lower K⁺; insulin/glucose and other K⁺-lowering agents are still required","Laboratory error — recheck","Pseudohyperkalemia from hemolysis"], answer:1,
      explanation:"Calcium raises the threshold for depolarization and buys you time against arrhythmia, but it does not shift or remove K⁺. You still need insulin + glucose (shift), albuterol (shift), and definitive removal (diuretics, K-binders, or dialysis). Knowing that calcium is membrane-stabilizing — not K-lowering — is a core teaching point." },
    { q:"A 24-year-old with new-onset polyuria and polydipsia has pH 7.18, pCO₂ 20, HCO₃⁻ 8, glucose 520, and anion gap 28. Is the respiratory compensation appropriate?",
      choices:["Inadequate — there is an additional respiratory acidosis","Appropriate","Excessive — there is a superimposed respiratory alkalosis","Cannot be determined from these values"], answer:1,
      explanation:"Winter's formula: expected pCO₂ = 1.5(HCO₃) + 8 ± 2 = 1.5(8) + 8 = 20 ± 2. Measured pCO₂ of 20 falls exactly within range — this is simple DKA with appropriate Kussmaul respiratory compensation. Any pCO₂ outside that window would signal a second acid-base process." },
    { q:"A trauma patient receives 5 L of 0.9% NaCl over 2 hours. Subsequent labs: pH 7.28, HCO₃⁻ 18, Cl⁻ 118, anion gap 10, lactate normal. The acid-base disturbance is best explained by:",
      choices:["Lactic acidosis from shock","Hyperchloremic non-anion-gap metabolic acidosis from the saline","AKI with retained fixed acids","DKA"], answer:1,
      explanation:"0.9% NaCl has 154 mEq/L of Cl⁻ (supraphysiologic). Large volumes dilute bicarb and drive up chloride — producing a predictable hyperchloremic, normal-AG metabolic acidosis. The SMART and SALT-ED trials showed balanced crystalloids (LR, Plasma-Lyte) reduce major adverse kidney events compared to high-volume NS." },
    { q:"A patient with eGFR 22 has Ca²⁺ 8.0, phosphorus 5.9, intact PTH 280, and 25-OH vitamin D 35 ng/mL (normal). Which best explains her secondary hyperparathyroidism?",
      choices:["Nutritional vitamin D deficiency","Reduced calcitriol from loss of renal 1-α-hydroxylase activity and FGF-23 suppression","Autonomous parathyroid adenoma","Calcium supplementation"], answer:1,
      explanation:"The 25-OH vitamin D (nutritional form) is normal, so deficiency is excluded. The damaged proximal tubule can't convert 25-OH D to active 1,25-(OH)₂D (calcitriol), and rising FGF-23 further suppresses 1-α-hydroxylase. The result is low active vitamin D, low calcium, and high phosphate — all stimulating PTH. Autonomous adenoma = tertiary hyperPTH." },
    { q:"A 32-year-old is found unresponsive. Labs: pH 7.10, HCO₃⁻ 6, anion gap 32, osmolar gap 38. The most likely ingestion is:",
      choices:["Aspirin","A toxic alcohol (methanol or ethylene glycol)","Acetaminophen","Iron"], answer:1,
      explanation:"An elevated anion gap metabolic acidosis PLUS an elevated osmolar gap is the classic fingerprint of toxic alcohol ingestion — methanol or ethylene glycol. Parent alcohol raises the osm gap; its metabolites (formic acid, glycolic/oxalic acid) produce the AG acidosis. Early fomepizole and dialysis are life-saving; don't wait for levels." },
  ],
  3: [
    { q:"A 45-year-old man presents with 3+ lower-extremity edema. Labs: UACR 4,200 mg/g (~5 g/day), serum albumin 2.3 g/dL, LDL 220. UA is bland without RBC casts. He meets criteria for:",
      choices:["Nephritic syndrome","Nephrotic syndrome","Isolated asymptomatic proteinuria","Orthostatic proteinuria"], answer:1,
      explanation:"Nephrotic syndrome requires the full pentad: >3.5 g/day proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, edema, hyperlipidemia, and (often) lipiduria. The bland sediment separates it from nephritic syndrome (hematuria, dysmorphic RBCs, RBC casts). Framing the syndrome correctly drives the biopsy differential and treatment." },
    { q:"A 22-year-old has recurrent episodes of gross hematuria that appear within 1–2 days of an upper respiratory infection. UA shows 3+ blood, 1+ protein, and dysmorphic RBCs. C3 and C4 are normal. Most likely diagnosis?",
      choices:["IgA nephropathy","Post-infectious glomerulonephritis","Thin basement membrane disease","Alport syndrome"], answer:0,
      explanation:"Synpharyngitic hematuria (concurrent with the URI — not 1–3 weeks later) plus normal complement levels is the signature of IgA nephropathy. Post-infectious GN has a 1–3 week latent period and low C3. Thin basement membrane disease causes persistent microscopic hematuria without gross episodes; Alport typically comes with hearing loss and family history." },
    { q:"A 58-year-old with type 2 diabetes has eGFR 48, UACR 400 mg/g, and clinic BP 142/88. He takes no antihypertensives. Which is the most appropriate first medication to initiate?",
      choices:["Hydrochlorothiazide","Amlodipine","ACE inhibitor or ARB","Metoprolol"], answer:2,
      explanation:"He checks every box for RAAS blockade: diabetes, albuminuria, elevated BP, and CKD. ACEi/ARBs reduce intraglomerular pressure and proteinuria and slow CKD progression. Modern KDIGO-aligned DKD care layers on an SGLT2 inhibitor next, followed by finerenone — but the RAAS blocker is still the foundation." },
    { q:"SGLT2 inhibitors and ACE inhibitors both slow CKD progression. They share which hemodynamic effect on the glomerulus?",
      choices:["Dilation of the efferent arteriole","Reduction in intraglomerular pressure","Blockade of aldosterone","Increased renal blood flow"], answer:1,
      explanation:"Both classes reduce intraglomerular pressure, but from opposite ends — ACEi/ARBs dilate the efferent arteriole, SGLT2i restore tubuloglomerular feedback and constrict the afferent arteriole. The shared net effect (and the shared initial ~3–5 mL/min eGFR 'dip') is why they are complementary pillars of CKD therapy." },
    { q:"A 70-year-old has a stable eGFR of 52 mL/min and UACR 320 mg/g across three visits. By KDIGO, her CKD classification is:",
      choices:["G2 A1","G3a A2","G3a A3","G3b A2"], answer:1,
      explanation:"KDIGO stages by both axes. eGFR 45–59 → G3a. UACR 30–300 → A2 (moderately increased). Her stage is G3a A2. Albuminuria adds major prognostic information independent of GFR — a G3a A3 patient has much higher risk than G3a A1, even at the same eGFR." },
    { q:"Which of the following patients is MOST likely to benefit from a kidney biopsy?",
      choices:["A 65-year-old with 20 years of T2DM, diabetic retinopathy, and a UACR slowly rising from 150 to 400 mg/g with bland sediment","A 35-year-old with 2 g/day proteinuria, dysmorphic RBCs, and Cr rising from 1.0 to 1.6 over 8 weeks","A 75-year-old with stable CKD stage 4 and Cr 3.0 unchanged for 2 years","A 40-year-old with isolated microscopic hematuria, normal Cr, and no proteinuria"], answer:1,
      explanation:"Biopsy is indicated when the diagnosis is unclear AND the result would change management. The 35-year-old has an unexplained GN-like picture (proteinuria + dysmorphic RBCs + rising Cr) — biopsy will define the specific lesion (IgA? lupus? ANCA? FSGS?) and drive therapy. The diabetic patient has textbook DKD — biopsy is usually unnecessary. Advanced stable CKD rarely benefits from biopsy (low yield, high risk). Isolated hematuria without proteinuria usually only needs urology evaluation and follow-up." },
  ],
  4: [
    { q:"A hospitalized patient with AKI and Cr 7.2 develops confusion, asterixis, and a new pericardial friction rub. K⁺ is 5.2, pH 7.32, and she is not volume overloaded. What is the correct indication for urgent dialysis?",
      choices:["Hyperkalemia","Refractory metabolic acidosis","Uremia with pericarditis and encephalopathy","None — continue medical management"], answer:2,
      explanation:"Of the AEIOU indications (Acidosis, Electrolytes, Ingestions, Overload, Uremia), this patient's trigger is the 'U' — uremic pericarditis is life-threatening and is an absolute indication for urgent dialysis regardless of K⁺ or pH. Don't anchor on K⁺ as the only reason to start RRT. Pericarditis, encephalopathy, and uremic bleeding each stand on their own." },
    { q:"A patient on chronic furosemide develops K⁺ 3.1 and metabolic alkalosis. Which best explains these combined findings?",
      choices:["Direct collecting-duct K⁺-sparing effect","NKCC2 inhibition in the thick ascending limb increases distal Na⁺ delivery → enhanced K⁺ and H⁺ secretion by principal/alpha-intercalated cells","Carbonic anhydrase inhibition causes bicarbonate wasting","Osmotic diuresis dehydrates the patient"], answer:1,
      explanation:"Loops block NKCC2 in the thick ascending limb (where ~25% of filtered Na⁺ is reabsorbed) — making them potent diuretics. The downstream consequence is more Na⁺ reaching the collecting duct, which trades for K⁺ and H⁺ secretion — producing hypokalemia AND a 'contraction' metabolic alkalosis. Understanding the mechanism lets you predict (and monitor for) these complications." },
    { q:"A patient receiving IV acyclovir for HSV encephalitis develops AKI on hospital day 2. Urine microscopy shows needle-shaped birefringent crystals. The most important preventive measure would have been:",
      choices:["Switching to oral rather than IV acyclovir","Ensuring generous IV hydration and a slower infusion rate","Adding probenecid","An age-based dose reduction"], answer:1,
      explanation:"Acyclovir precipitates in the tubular lumen when urine flow is low or the drug bolus is concentrated — the classic 'crystal nephropathy.' Prevention is volume-dependent: aggressive isotonic hydration and slower infusion (over at least 1 hour). Other crystal-forming agents to recognize: methotrexate, sulfonamides, indinavir, atazanavir, high-dose vitamin C." },
    { q:"A peritoneal dialysis patient develops a new right-sided pleural effusion. Diagnostic thoracentesis shows fluid glucose of 480 mg/dL — nearly matching her dialysate glucose. The most likely mechanism is:",
      choices:["Right heart failure","A pleuroperitoneal communication (diaphragmatic defect) allowing dialysate to track into the pleural space","Chemical serositis from dialysate components","Parapneumonic effusion"], answer:1,
      explanation:"A high-glucose pleural effusion in a PD patient — often right-sided, often appearing soon after starting PD — is the classic pleuroperitoneal communication. Dialysate tracks through a diaphragmatic defect into the pleural space. Diagnosis is clinched by fluid glucose >300 (well above serum). Management: stop PD temporarily; many close spontaneously, but some need surgical repair or transition to hemodialysis." },
    { q:"A kidney transplant recipient on tacrolimus develops a Cr rise from 1.3 to 1.8. His tacrolimus trough is 14 ng/mL (target 8–10). After a dose reduction, Cr returns to 1.4 within a week. This reversible pattern reflects:",
      choices:["Acute cellular rejection","Dose-dependent afferent arteriolar vasoconstriction from the CNI","BK virus nephropathy","Recurrent primary disease"], answer:1,
      explanation:"Calcineurin inhibitors cause afferent vasoconstriction → reduced renal blood flow → a rapid, dose-dependent, REVERSIBLE GFR drop. Chronic CNI exposure instead causes irreversible 'striped' interstitial fibrosis and tubular atrophy. Acute rejection would not improve with a dose reduction; BK nephropathy requires PCR and biopsy for diagnosis." },
  ],
};

